mangle
======

A structured H.265 (HEVC) bitstream fuzzer for security research.

This product includes work inspired by and built on top of the following.


Design inspiration
------------------

h26forge
  Vasudev Bhaskaran, Sam Crow, Hovav Shacham, et al.,
  "h26forge: Generating Syntactically Correct but Semantically Spec-Non-Compliant
  H.264 Video Files," USENIX Security 2024.
  https://www.usenix.org/conference/usenixsecurity24

  mangle adopts h26forge's core idea — generating syntactically-correct but
  semantically spec-non-compliant video bitstreams via structured, parameter-level
  mutation — and applies it to H.265 (HEVC), which the h26forge paper explicitly
  identified as a fuzzing gap. mangle reuses no h26forge source code; only the
  design approach is shared.


Decoders (used, not bundled)
----------------------------

ffmpeg
  https://ffmpeg.org/
  Licensed under the GNU LGPL/GPL. mangle invokes ffmpeg as an external decode
  target via subprocess; it does not bundle, link, or modify ffmpeg.

libde265
  https://github.com/strukturag/libde265
  An open-source HEVC decoder. mangle can invoke libde265's `dec265` CLI as a
  decode target; it does not bundle, link, or modify libde265.


HEVC patent acknowledgment
--------------------------

H.265 / HEVC is an ITU-T / ISO-IEC standard covered by patents licensed through
pools including MPEG LA / Access Advance and others. mangle does NOT implement an
HEVC encoder or decoder. It reads, mutates, and writes HEVC bitstream syntax for
the express purpose of security research, and feeds the resulting bitstreams to
pre-existing, separately-obtained decoders (ffmpeg / libde265). See README.md for
the full research-purpose statement.
